						<p>
				For put options, in-the-money means that strike price is above the actual stock price. Example: An investor purchases a put option at the $110 strike price for XYZ that is currently trading at $100. This investor position is in-the-money by $10. The put option gives the investor the right to sell the equity at $110. At the money (ATM)			</p>

